            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this trip cost calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This trip cost calculator is designed to give you a realistic,
                itemized budget for road trips and vacations. Unlike simple
                fuel-only tools, it includes fuel, tolls, lodging, food, parking
                and other extras, and shows both the total and per-person cost.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Fuel cost</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator supports both MPG and L/100 km, and both price
                per gallon and per liter.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Normalize units</strong></p>
                <p>If distance is in km, it is converted to miles:</p>
                <p>\(\text{miles} = \text{km} \times 0.621371\)</p>
                <p>If fuel economy is in L/100 km, it is converted to MPG:</p>
                <p>\(\text{MPG} = \dfrac{235.215}{\text{L/100 km}}\)</p>
                <p>
                  If fuel price is per liter, it is converted to price per
                  gallon:
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{price/gal} = \text{price/L} \times 3.78541\)</p>
                <hr />
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Fuel needed</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{gallons} = \dfrac{\text{distance
                  (miles)}}{\text{MPG}}\)
                </p>
                <hr />
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Fuel cost</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{fuel cost} = \text{gallons} \times \text{price per
                  gallon}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Lodging and food</h3>
              <p>
                Lodging cost is simply the nightly rate multiplied by the number
                of nights. Food and other daily costs are based on the estimated
                number of trip days and the number of travelers.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{lodging cost} = \text{nights} \times \text{lodging per
                  night}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{food cost} = \text{trip days} \times \text{food per
                  day per person} \times \text{travelers}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{other daily cost} = \text{trip days} \times
                  \text{other daily per person} \times \text{travelers}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Trip days are estimated from driving time and nights. Driving
                time is distance divided by average speed. The tool converts
                hours to days and then adds nights as full days. If you enter a
                manual trip length in days, that value overrides the automatic
                estimate.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Tolls, parking and other fixed costs</h3>
              <p>
                Tolls, parking and other fixed costs are added directly to the
                total. These are not multiplied by days or travelers.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{extras} = \text{tolls} + \text{parking} + \text{other
                  fixed}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Total and per-person cost</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{total cost} = \text{fuel} + \text{lodging} +
                  \text{food} + \text{other daily} + \text{extras}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{cost per person} = \dfrac{\text{total
                  cost}}{\text{number of travelers}}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Tips for more accurate trip budgeting</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use real fuel economy:</strong> Base MPG on your
                  actual driving or on long-term trip computer data.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check current fuel prices:</strong> Use prices along
                  your route, not just at home.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Be conservative with lodging:</strong> Add a buffer
                  for taxes, resort fees and parking.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Include activities:</strong> Put tickets, tours and
                  attractions into “Other fixed costs” or “Other daily cost”.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Plan for contingencies:</strong> Add 5–15% on top of
                  the estimate for unexpected expenses.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Can I use this for international trips?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Enter distance in miles or kilometers, fuel economy in MPG
                or L/100 km, and fuel price in your local currency per gallon or
                liter. All results will be in the same currency you used for
                fuel and other costs.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I estimate tolls?</h3>
              <p>
                For the most accurate tolls, use a map or toll-specific service
                to get a total for your route, then enter that amount in the
                tolls field. If you only have a rough idea, it is better to
                overestimate slightly.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this include vehicle wear and depreciation?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The calculator focuses on out-of-pocket trip expenses: fuel,
                lodging, food and fees. If you want to include wear and
                depreciation, you can add an extra amount per mile or per day
                into the “Other fixed costs” or “Other daily cost per person”
                fields.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my trip has multiple vehicles?</h3>
              <p>
                Run the calculator once per vehicle and add the totals, or
                approximate a combined fuel economy and total number of
                travelers, then use that single run as a quick estimate.
              </p>
            </section>
